  "prompt": "Where can I rent a big apartment in Seattle and not pay too much money?",
  "response": "Finding a big apartment in Seattle without breaking the bank can be challenging, but it\u2019s possible with some strategic searching. Here are some tips and neighborhoods to consider for affordable, spacious rentals:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Look Outside the City Center**\n- **Northgate**: Offers more affordable options with decent-sized apartments and access to light rail.\n- **Rainier Valley**: Includes neighborhoods like Columbia City, which are more affordable and have larger units.\n- **West Seattle**: Rentals can be more spacious and affordable compared to downtown, especially in areas like Delridge.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Consider Older Buildings**\nOlder apartment buildings often offer larger units at lower prices compared to newer constructions. Look for pre-war buildings or complexes built in the 1960s\u20131980s.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Check Out the Suburbs**\n- **Shoreline**: Just north of Seattle, offers more space for less money.\n- **Burien**: South of the city, known for relatively affordable rents.\n- **Tukwila**: Offers larger apartments and is close to public transit.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Use Rental Tools and Websites**\n- **Craigslist**: Look for private landlords who may offer better deals.\n- **HotPads**: Allows you to filter by size (sq. ft.) and price.\n- **Zillow Rentals**: Search for larger apartments in affordable neighborhoods.\n- **Facebook Marketplace**: Local listings can sometimes have hidden gems.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Be Flexible on Neighborhoods**\nSome affordable neighborhoods with potential for larger apartments include:\n- **White Center**: Up-and-coming area with more affordable rents.\n- **Beacon Hill**: Offers a mix of affordability and larger spaces.\n- **Lake City**: Known for lower rents and larger units.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Negotiate Rent or Look for Deals**\n- Ask about move-in specials or discounts for signing a longer lease.\n- Consider renting during off-peak seasons (winter months) when prices may be lower.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Consider Roommates**\nIf you're open to sharing space, splitting a larger apartment with roommates can significantly reduce costs.\n\n---\n\n### **Example Budget-Friendly Neighborhoods**\n- **Columbia City**: Diverse, affordable, and still close to the city.\n- **Greenwood**: Offers larger units and a community feel.\n- **Delridge** (West Seattle): More space for less money.\n\n---\n\n### **Pro Tip**\nExpand your search to include \"2-bedroom apartments\" even if you only need one bedroom. Often, a 2-bedroom in a less expensive area can cost the same as a 1-bedroom in a more central location.\n\nBy being flexible and exploring these options, you can find a spacious apartment in Seattle without overspending. Happy hunting!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
